Simulate AR + ARCH Model

1. If the model is AR(1) + ARCH(1), then \(y_t = \phi * y_{t-1} + \eta_t\) (where \(\eta_t\) follows an ARCH(1) model)
2. Then \(\eta_t = \sigma_t * \epsilon_t\) where \(\sigma_t^2 = \omega + \alpha_1 \eta_{t-1}^2 + \beta_1 \sigma^2_{t-1}\)
Load required libraries.

library(TSA)
library(fGarch)
#set.seed(13204942)

Firstly, we need to initialize hyperparameters:

u = 1 # AR order
v = 0 # MA order
p = 1 # GARCH order
q = 1 # GARCH order
# sampling coefficients
samp_coefs = function(l){
  vec = rep(0,l)
  for(i in 1:l){
    vec[i] = runif(1, 0, 1) * sample(c(-1,1), 1)
  }
  return(vec)
}

Setup fixed values of parameters.

mu = 0 # (the linear part) the mean value, by default NULL
omega = 0.1 # the constant coefficient of the variance equation (default 1e-6)
alpha = 0.2
beta = 0.5
phi = 0.6
#alpha;phi

# length of time series
n = 300

# alpha = 0; if (p > 0) alpha = samp_coefs(p) # the values of AR coefficients
# beta = 0; if (q > 0) beta = samp_coefs(q) # the values of variance coefficients
# phi = 0; if (u > 0) phi = samp_coefs(u) # the values of AR coefficients (ARIMA)

Simulate the GARCH(1,1) model for \(\eta\) with parameters.

# GARCH(1,1)
spec = garchSpec(model = list(mu = 0, omega = omega, alpha = alpha, beta = beta))
#spec = garchSpec(model = list(mu = 0, omega = 0.01, alpha = 0.5, beta = beta))
eta = garchSim(spec, n)
# use simulated eta to simulate a AR(1) model
ts = arima.sim(list(ar = phi), n, innov = eta$garch)
plot(ts, t='l')

Simulate Multiple Time Series

K = 20  # simulate 30 time series
multi_series = matrix(NA, K, n)
series_param = matrix(NA, nrow = K, ncol = 6)
colnames(series_param) <- c("u", "phi1", "phi2", "phi3", "autocorrelation", "accepted")
# confidence interval
ci = c(-1.96/sqrt(n), 1.96/sqrt(n))
lags = 20
# GARCH(1,1)
spec = garchSpec(model = list(mu = mu, omega = omega, alpha = alpha, beta = beta))
eta = garchSim(spec, n)
# multiple time series share the same eta_t part
for(k in 1:K){
  skip_to_next <- FALSE
  # generate u randomly
  u = sample(c(1,2,3), 1, replace = TRUE)
  series_param[k,1] = u
  
  # the values of AR coefficients (ARIMA)
  phi = 0; if (u > 0) phi = samp_coefs(u)
  series_param[k,2:(u+1)] = phi
  
  possibleError <- tryCatch({
    # use shared eta to simulate a AR(u) model
    multi_series[k,] = arima.sim(list(ar = phi), n, innov = eta$garch)
    
    # ACF
    series_ro <- acf(multi_series[k,], lag.max = lags, plot = FALSE)
    series_param[k,5] <- sum(series_ro$acf > ci[1])
    series_param[k,6] <- 1
    }, 
    error = function(e) {
      e
      print(paste("Skip the non-stationary series in loop ",k,sep = ""))
      })
  
  if(inherits(possibleError, "error")) next
}

Identify the orders of \(AR(u)\) components. Create a function to identify the orders.

order_identifier <- function(afc_pacf, lags){
  p_hat <- 1
  q_hat <- 1

  for(l in (2:lags)){
    if(abs(afc_pacf[,'acf'][l]) > ci[2]){
      q_hat = q_hat + 1
    }
    else{
      break
    }
  }
  
  for(l in (2:lags)){
    if(abs(afc_pacf[,'pacf'][l]) > ci[2]){
      p_hat = p_hat + 1
    }
    else{
      break
    }
  }  
  return(list(p_hat = p_hat, q_hat = q_hat))
}
#acf_order <- lags - sum(abs(ro$acf) < ci[2])
#pacf_order <- lags - sum(abs(phi$acf) < ci[2])
# the order u is equal to the number of PACF 
#u <- pacf_order
acf_matrix <- cbind(ro$acf, phi$acf)
colnames(acf_matrix) <- c('acf','pacf')
arma_orders <- order_identifier(acf_matrix, lags)
arma_orders$p_hat

## [1] 4

This shows that the \(GARCH(p,q)\) model for the return series implies that the model for the squared returns is an \(ARMA(max(p,q),p)\) model. Thus, we can apply the model identification techniques for ARMA models to the squared return series to identify p and \(max(p,q)\). In this case, the target series \(GARCH\) component is \(GARCH(1,1)\).

Create a function to calculate ACF and PACF.

acf_identifier <- function(x, lags){
  # ACF
  ro <- acf(x, lag.max = lags, plot = FALSE)
  # PACF
  phi <- pacf(x, lag.max = lags, plot = FALSE)
  
  return(cbind(acf = ro$acf, pacf = phi$acf))
}
x <- res.ts^2
# ACF and PACF

#pacf_order <- lags - sum(abs(arch_identify[,'pacf']) < ci[2])

garch_orders <- order_identifier(arch_identify, lags)

Identify Multiple Models

Identify \(u\) and \(v\) for each series separately. Now select one series as an example to demo.

target_series <- multi_series[series_index,]
N <- nrow(target_series)
lags <- 15
acf_matrix <- matrix(NA, ncol = 2, nrow = lags, dimnames = list(NULL,c('acf','pacf')))
estimate_orders <- matrix(NA, ncol = 2, nrow = N, dimnames = list(NULL,c('p_hat','q_hat')))
residuals_matrix <- matrix(NA, ncol = n, nrow = N)

for(index in (1:N)){
  tar_ts <- target_series[index,]
  
  # ACF
  ro <- acf(tar_ts, lag.max = lags, plot = FALSE)
  # PACF
  phi <- pacf(tar_ts, lag.max = lags, plot = FALSE)
  
  acf_matrix[,'acf'] <- as.vector(ro$acf)
  acf_matrix[,'pacf'] <- as.vector(phi$acf)
  arma_orders <- order_identifier(acf_matrix, lags)  
  estimate_orders[index,] <- c(arma_orders$p_hat, arma_orders$q_hat)
  
  # assumption: series has AR component
  fit_ts = arima(tar_ts, order = c(arma_orders$p_hat,0,0))
  x = residuals(fit_ts)  
  residuals_matrix[index,] <- x
}

kaike’s Information Criterion (AIC), which was useful in selecting predictors for regression, is also useful for determining the order of an ARIMA model. Good models are obtained by minimising the AIC. The \(GARCH(1,1)\) returns smaller AIC, so it is selected.
